Inflation in Europe has skyrocketed because of food
The accelerating inflation measured in the euro area is mainly due to the constant rise in food prices.
November price growth in the 13 eurozone countries was higher than expected, with annual inflation of 3.1% recorded in October after 2.6%, the Union Statistical Office in Luxembourg reported.
The official forecast was only 3 percent, Bloomberg reported.
Unlike the American, British and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) did not reduce the base rate, saying that a reduction, combined with rising commodity prices and falling unemployment, would lead to an inflationary spiral.
The ECB would like to keep inflation below 2%, but close to that.
One analyst said that the ECB was in an absurd situation: it had to "prevent" inflation so that it would not have to do anything about it later.
In Germany, November inflation of 3.3 percent was a 15-year high; in Spain, it rose from 3.6 to 4.1 percent.
Inflation in the euro area has soared due to sharply rising food and energy prices.
Wheat futures rose 88 percent, and the soybean price reached its highest level since 1973.
Similarly, in 2007, edible oil and dairy products had to be paid significantly more.
The price of oil on world markets has risen 52 percent this year, and last month a barrel of black gold was already selling for nearly $100.
According to the ECB, inflation will jump to 2.5% in 2008 from 2.1% in 2008 but will already fall to 1.9% in 2009.
Analysts expect inflation to remain at around 3 percent for the next three to four months, but at an average annual rate of 2.1 percent.
At the same time, they expect the ECB to cut interest rates twice in 2008.
Gallup sees a government crisis
The support base for Fidesz has grown significantly since its initial stagnation in early December, and it now has the largest support base since 2002, while the Socialists have never had such low support as the -13% that the Gallup Institute has measured.
For some party voters, the difference - due to the greater determination of the opposition voters - would represent more than two-thirds (71%) support versus one-fifth support for the MSZP.
The MDF and the SZDSZ are below the threshold for entry to parliament, according to the survey: their support within the population is two percent.
Among some party voters, the two sides are one percent more likely to support each other.
Public opinion of the economy has also deteriorated from the previous low - never before has the proportion of those who consider the country's economic situation to be very bad been so high - 41 percent, while another 46 percent believe the situation is quite bad.
Families are now more pessimistic about their material situation after the more hopeful outlook of spring and summer.
As for next year, most of the population expects further deterioration and only a tenth expects improvement.
In December, 71 percent of those polled, the highest number of any Gallup poll to date, said the prime minister was doing a bad job rather than a good job.
Ferenc Gyurcsány is trusted or very trusted by 13 percent of those surveyed, while Viktor Orbán's share of supporters is 38 percent.
The Prime Minister is not trusted at all by 54 percent, the leader of the Fidesz movement by 27 percent.
One of the indicators of the political situation is how much of the public believes that the dissatisfaction with the Prime Minister can be resolved without a change of government.
While 35 percent of those who had considered the continuation of the government and the prime minister desirable after last October's unrest, this number is now only 20 percent, with a relative majority (33 percent) seeing the solution only in calling new elections.
Significantly, 60 percent of respondents said they would certainly attend the referendum and another 20 percent said they would probably attend.
For comparison, only 55 percent would definitely participate in "parliamentary elections this Sunday" and another 15 percent consider their participation likely.
School fees would be 74 percent, doctor fees 79 percent, and hospital fees 84 percent.
If we look at the same percentages only in the circle of people who certainly promise to participate, then the introduction of tuition, doctor's fees and hospital fees would be rejected by 81, 84 and 89 percent.
The most expensive is Auchan, almost a fifth over Tesco
The hypermarkets in the Budaörs Triangle retained last year's average price level of 16% with the difference that there was no VAT increase this year.
Article from the Napi Gazdaság newspaper
The usual Christmas shopping basket of Napi Gazdaság newspaper in the Budauer shopping triangle has increased by an average of 16 percent this year, but in all hypermarkets the price has increased by more than a thousand forints.
Since food prices in supermarkets "surged" last December, the percentage increase was not as drastic as the previous high base.
But it is certainly unpleasant for the consumer that what he could buy for less than nine thousand forints last year, he cannot buy for ten thousand.
The daily economy shopping basket in the hypermarkets examined exceeded the psychological limit of 10 000 forints by at least 91 forints.
The highest price of the basket was 10,573 forints.
(In 2003, the cost of a basket was HUF 6,800.)
The price of Unica and live fish has stayed almost at last year's level, but the price of breast, nuts and poppy have gone up.
The prices of bread and flour were in line with the Central Statistical Office, although in Auchan we found a kilo of bread for 139 forints.
The competition didn't go below 200 forints.
Also surprising in this store was the fact that the price of a two-liter Coca-Cola in a return bottle was under 200 forints, so even with the deposit the product cost only 257 forints.
However, according to the Napi Gazdaság daily's consumption basket, Auchan was the most expensive, while Cora was the cheapest.
According to our calculations, the prices in the Napi Gazdaság shopping cart have increased by 15 percent compared to last year's Christmas sales of Cora, while Tesco and Auchan have increased by approximately 18 percent.
When you compare last year's high and this year's low, the difference between the low and the high was 12 percent, while the increase between last year's low and this year's high is 21 percent.
In forints, the average increase was 1,480
The average price increase last year was HUF 1 206 with prices affected by the VAT increase at Christmas.
This process has disrupted trade, and the trading houses have clearly been unable to decide how wide a price range to set for each product, since they have been unable to predict the effect of changes in prices on consumption.
(If a trader plans the turnover rate of a given product poorly, significant profits may be lost due to the price range adjusted to the turnover intensity.)
Because of the VAT, the price of the Napi Gazdaság consumer basket last year was so extreme that the price of the most expensive basket was HUF 1,720 higher than in 2006, while the price difference for the cheapest basket was HUF 844.
This year, the extreme difference was not apparent, the most expensive basket was now 1630 forints more than last year and the cheapest basket was also 1,284 forints more expensive.
When comparing the two Christmas seasons, the price increase was catastrophic, with daily groceries in supermarkets rising by more than 30 percent in less than 20 months.
(This, among other things, is not absolutely confirmed by the Central Statistical Office data: it measured price increases of more than 30 percent over 12 months for several staple foods.
In addition to flour, for example, eggs.)
In the latter case, however, this seems almost impossible according to the Daily Economy's consumption basket, since the price level of the product, already quite expensive last year, showed a price increase of barely 10% in the worst case, compared to the base.
Flour suppliers seem to be in a stronger position than egg suppliers, and they have managed to push through the drastic price increases in international chains.
The hypermarkets in the Golden Triangle of Commerce aren't complaining, they're still reporting a good year.
In our experience, most customers in the three stores we visited no longer care about prices.
They buy everything in quantity, take perishables for a fee.
On Wednesday morning, long lines were formed at the checkout counters in all three supermarkets because of the surge in the number of visitors.
But as we know, the rural areas have lower revenues, and many international chains have complained to research firms that sales are falling short of their plans, not only for food but also for durable consumer goods.
Many places are saving on disinfectants
This year, more than a thousand hospital infections were reported, mostly due to inappropriate antibiotic use.
Hygienic conditions in hospitals, overcrowded beds, overcrowded personnel to contain the disease are not helping, says the head of the National Epidemiological Center.
In many places, too, disinfectants are being used sparingly.
Recently, an MRSA infection was diagnosed in the trauma department of St. John's Hospital.
Antibiotic-resistant bacteria have been discovered in a man who was admitted to hospital after a serious car accident.
The patient has been isolated.
A similar infection occurred in the same place earlier this year.
A patient who had been injured in a serious car accident was discharged, but soon afterward he was returned with MRSA infection, and a major operation had not yet been performed because of the bacteria in his system.
As of December 10, 1,094 hospital infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens have been reported to the National Nesocomialis Surveillance System, according to Karolina Böröczová, a senior official at the National Epidemiology Centre.
This means that so many infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens have been recorded in hospitals with certainty, others are not known.
Almost two thirds (683) of the infections were caused by MRSA, or methicillin-resistant staphylococcus aureus.
Staphylococcus aureus (SA) is carried by one third of the population through the nose without causing any disease.
Infections caused by SA (e. g. strep throat, tonsillitis, skin infections, morning infections) respond well to antibiotics and are well treatable.
However, if antibiotics are over- or inappropriately administered, bacteria that respond well to antibiotics will develop into bacteria that are highly resistant to antibiotics and that spread rapidly in unsuitable hospital conditions.
In particular, in the case of temporary or permanent immune dysfunction in patients with weakened bodies, low body weight or in elderly patients, it can cause serious hospital infections such as morning infections or sepsis.
According to the chief medical officer of St. John's, there is nothing special about MRSA infection, as it is a common practice in hospitals.
"Infection must not be confused with epidemic, MRSA is not the only place", declared Tibor Nyulasi, "where the presence of a disease-causing agent is not investigated".
Resistant to antibiotics
"We isolate these patients, the nursing staff treats them in rubber gloves and masks, and we have the necessary antibiotics to treat them", said Tibor Nyulasi.
Patients admitted to hospital are first tested for MRSA, but infection cannot always be avoided.
Sampling is out of fashion
The vast majority of hospital infections caused by MRSA could be prevented, but the current conditions in domestic hospitals are not conducive to preventing the emergence and spread of multidrug-resistant pathogens, says Karolina Böröczová.
Since this infection is symptomatically present in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should monitor patients admitted and isolate MRSA carriers immediately.
However, microbiological sampling is not a new trend in Hungarian hospitals.
The fact that the National Health Insurance Fund does not fund this investigation also plays a role.
Most cases are detected when the patient has a detectable MRSA infection, said the epidemiology center's primary investigator.
The European Union has strict guidelines for appropriate treatment of antibiotics in human medicine, and there are also domestic guidelines for the treatment of individual infections, pathology.
Efforts should be made to target antibiotic therapy or to conduct microbiological testing to prevent the development of drug resistance, but this is not always the case in hospitals.
The Commission is also proposing to introduce a new system of controls on the use of the euro in the healthcare sector.
Saves on disinfectants
Scientific evidence suggests that MRSA is most commonly transmitted to patients through healthcare personnel.
So handwashing and the use of gloves and masks play a very important role, but even in this there are serious shortcomings in hospitals.
MRSA is transmitted by droplet infection and contact, but it is not always possible to isolate infected patients in home hospital settings.
On the contrary, the rooms are often crowded, the beds are often very close together, although from an epidemiological point of view patients should be at least 1.5 meters apart.
As Karolina Böröcz noted, unfortunately, hospitals with a poor financial situation often lack disinfectants, few nurses, and many patients, thus increasing the risk of infection.
According to Karolina Böröcz, where the necessary protective measures are observed, there is a demonstrable reduction in similar infections or further spread of the disease-causing organism can be stopped.
The government's MRSA program
Treating MRSA infection is a huge expense for health insurance companies, which is why it is being fought everywhere.
In England, for example, the government has set up a programme to prevent MRSA, or to reduce its incidence.
The programme seems to be successful, as the published data shows that MRSA infections in England are on the decline.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) has identified as a priority the prevention of multi-resistant pathogens (including MRSA) and of hospital infections caused by these pathogens.
The police captain who caused the fatal accident was not drunk
The official expert opinion in the case of the police captain of the XXII district who caused the fatal accident is finished.
It is impossible that the police captain of the XXII district, who killed a pedestrian on Tuesday and who has since resigned from his post, was driving under the influence of alcohol or drugs, informed the spokesman of the High State Representative Office of the capital Attila Morvai on Friday after the expert assessment of the case was completed.
The forensic assessment confirmed the result of the initial investigation, which had already established that the former police captain had no alcohol before he got behind the wheel.
The then-Director of the XXII District Police Department, on Tuesday, in the street Lajos Kossuth in the XXII District, hit a man of fifty-five, who had stepped in front of him, crossing the road outside the marked crossing, with his own car, while turning the corner.
(The latter fact of the pedestrian crossing the crossing is not an extenuating circumstance, according to the rules of the road, the turning car must still give priority.)
After being transported to the hospital, the pedestrian died.
The incident led to the district police chief resigning and requesting a transfer to a retirement position, reportedly because he was so shaken by the case.
The case is being investigated by the Budapest Prosecutor's Office.
Attila Morvai also mentioned that the former police captain had cooperated with the prosecutors carrying out the investigation from the beginning.
