Bulgaria is the real estate paradise of the EU
The development of the Bulgarian real estate market is astonishing - the attention of all Europe is turning to the previously slightly neglected Balkan country.
What, where and who are buying in the EU's ever-cheapest but fast-growing market?
The analysis of the Bulgarian division of Re/Max.
Bulgaria, with its cheap ski apartments and seaside villas, is now without doubt the most sought-after East European destination for property purchases.
The mountains are the most in the course area of Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitoša, on the sea coast Albena, Zlaté Piesky, Sunny Coast, the ancient cities of Sozopol and Nesebar, but more and more people are also looking for real estate in the vicinity of Kavarna and Balchik.
According to analysts from Re/Max Bulgaria, sooner or later investors will also be interested in the central part of the country - such as Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, Triavna - and more and more people are also buying in the surroundings of the cheap city of Ruse.
The capital Sofia also promises attractive opportunities, with commercial and office space offering the highest returns.
Bulgaria is well on its way to becoming one of Europe's most attractive golfing paradises, becoming a popular destination for the next two seasons, in addition to the summer and winter seasons.
Forward-looking investors are already buying in bulk, for example in the Banska area.
According to analysts, property buyers in Bulgaria are also trying to change their lives and lifestyles.
The largest number of customers comes from England, but there are also buyers from France, Belgium, Spain and, increasingly, Romania.
There are also Maltese and Cypriot investors, and there are traditionally many Russian customers in the Black Sea and in the ski resorts.
Foreign buyers can be divided into three groups, says Georgij Yankov, regional director of Re/Max Bulgaria.
Settlers buy either renovated properties worth 50-100 thousand euros or dilapidated old houses for 5-15 thousand euros, which they then renovate.
They require good accessibility and communication, and they are close to the big city, shops and, as a rule, a local doctor.
The second category is that of the cottage-buyers (Bulgaria ranked among the top 10 German holiday destinations in December).
The third group consists of commercial investors who buy in the hope of a rise in value in the medium or long term.
Real estate auctions in the capital are continuous, as demand is growing stronger and stronger.
Bulgaria has the lowest real estate prices in the European Union, yet it has grown by 21 percent annually over the past five years.
The increase in real estate prices is significantly outpacing the growth in wages.
Fedor and Hungarian six percent
According to Minister of Environment and Water, Gábor Fodor, expert meetings will end on Tuesday and the post-2012 international climate conference will continue with ministerial discussions after the official opening on Wednesday.
Experts and policymakers from 192 countries are discussing the Bali Roadmap, which addresses the efforts following the emissions reduction period set by the Kyoto Protocol until 2012.
At the moment, there is a heated debate between developing and developed countries.
The United States also said it did not want to negotiate precise figures at this time, although it is committed to a deal to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 25-40 percent by 2020 compared to 1990 levels.
Another big question at the conference is whether developed countries will agree to provide both material and technological assistance to countries that rely on them, in addition to reducing emissions.
The agreement also established subsidies for developing countries.
The grant fund, set up by the Kyoto Protocol, will be managed by a 16-member steering committee, presumably within the framework of the UN's Global Environment Facility (GEF).
Hungarian six percent
The Minister for the Environment and Water, Gábor Fodor, has supported Hungary's efforts to maintain the EU's leadership role in global climate protection and to help forge a new international agreement by 2009.
The minister said that the EU is committed to reducing greenhouse gas emissions by 20 per cent below 1990 levels by 2020, irrespective of the success of the 'post-2012 agreement', and is ready to commit to reductions of up to 30 per cent if other developed regions of the world, or developed countries, are willing to take on responsibilities and commitments commensurate with their capabilities.
Gábor Fodor pointed out that the countries that joined the Kyoto Protocol in 1997 set a reduction target of 5.2%, while the then 15 EU Member States committed to 8%.
Hungary's commitment to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6 percent compared to 1985-87 is a reality. - as stated in the press release of the Ministry of Environment.
Bali is a big deal, because an international agreement on long-term climate change policy must be adopted within two years, or its entry into force would be postponed until 2012. In such a case, the reduction commitments set out in the Kyoto Protocol would not be immediately followed by a new emission reduction system, the necessity of which was also pointed out by the UN's International Panel on Climate Change - the Nobel Peace Prize winner - in its latest report.
This would delay the reduction of emissions and inevitably increase the average temperature of the Earth by more than 2 degrees Celsius, which scientists say would have extremely serious and irreversible consequences.
The British Army is conducting a recruitment on YouTube
British military units are posting on a video sharing server footage of their actions in Iraq and Afghanistan to promote themselves.
YouTube first caught the eye of the RAF: Special Forces operating in Afghanistan have been uploading videos of anti-Taliban actions since March 2006, the BBC reported.
The footage, taken by a miniature camera attached to a helmet, is monitored by the air force command operating combat operations in the Kandahar area and then sent on to London, where it is broadcast on the Internet.
The political message is inevitable
In this form, 139 recordings of British airmen have been posted online, and their "channel" has been viewed by over 75,000 people.
The British Ministry of Defence registered in the spring of 2007 as "defenceheadquarters" and publishes recordings of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan, while the British Foreign Office (Commonwealth Office) and the International Peace Facility in Iraq (MNFI) have their own YouTube channels.
Deployed in Afghanistan
The Air Force has released videos of its original intent for recruitment, and according to the Department of Defense, they are also good at informing the general public about the true purpose of the military presence overseas.
"The advertisement in this form costs next to nothing compared to traditional television recruitment ads", said Gordon Mackenzie, a defense expert, to the BBC, "but it also necessarily carries a political message, as it confirms the legitimacy of military action decided by the government".
The Americans made a play
The army is concerned that besides the carefully edited, censored recordings, amateur videos are also being uploaded to the server, depicting the death of soldiers, for example: in a somewhat hypocritical, "official" promotional film, officers talk about losses, but do not show the bloody aspect of the battle.
There's a lot of video on the internet of the battlefields of Iraq and Afghanistan, of the heavy deployments, but the British military have only just discovered them.
The Americans do the recruiting a little differently - with a free-to-download shooter called America's Army, in which the player can get into the soldiers' skin through a more or less faithful simulation.
