It's coming up to a giant strike.
The League of Trade Unions and the National Union of Workers' Councils (MOSZ) will form their strike committee on Friday to coordinate the Monday strike for an indefinite period.
There's a protest rally on Saturday, and a work stoppage on Monday, the final day of the health care bill vote.
The action will certainly cause serious disruption to transport, as almost all rail transport will be stopped and the employees of the Budapest Transport Company (BKV) will also strike by 1 p.m.
On Friday afternoon, the League and the National Union of Workers' Councils will announce the details of the joint strike on Monday.
A strike committee will be formed to coordinate the action.
On Saturday, there's a public protest meeting, and on Monday, the unions joining the strike will stop work indefinitely unless an agreement is reached with the government.
This means that there is no date set for the end of the strike, which will begin on the day of the parliamentary vote on the health insurance bill.
If the health insurance bill is not passed by Parliament, the unions will immediately withdraw the strike.
However, if the legislation is voted down, the strike committee will meet and decide on the next step.
The Monday agenda of the Parliament also allows for the health insurance bill to be voted on late in the evening or at night.
Due to the strike starting on Monday, there are likely to be major disruptions to transportation: work on the railway will be stopped indefinitely, part of Budapest's public transport and more than half of Volán's companies may stop in the morning.
At the same time, in many parts of the country, half the roadways will also be closed.
The call for the strike was joined by numerous unions and civil organizations, whose list is constantly updated on the League's website.
Some organizations have called for an indefinite strike, others have declared temporary stoppages.
