The Hungarian doctors' union will strike alternately throughout the country, the Democratic Union of Healthcare and Social Workers (EDDSZ), belonging to the Cooperation Forum of Trade Unions (SZEF), is holding a two-hour warning strike.
The most important of the four demands made by the League is for the government to withdraw its health insurance reform proposal and present a new concept for public discussion.
The second requirement is that the new method of calculating pensions be introduced gradually from next year.
Third, to ensure that early retirement for the relevant occupational fields is possible before 2010.
The fourth reason for the action is that the Independent Trade Union of Railway Employees (VDSZSZ), which is part of the League, does not accept the offer of the Ministry of Economy and Transport regarding the railway branches and is waiting for another offer.
Political Capital: Hungarian Guard has increased the risk of the country
The Hungarian Guard, which was founded with the support of the Jobbik Magyarországért movement in August this year, has increased the political risk of Hungary and the region in several ways, according to the Risk Analysing Division of the Political Capital Institute.
The 'risk warning' prepared by the firm states that the biggest political risk in relation to the activities of the Hungarian Guard is that 'the already existing ethnic tension between the Roma and non-Roma population of Hungary may escalate into violent ethnic clashes in the short term'.
The main reason is that the political strategy of the Hungarian Guard is likely to provoke such an action - adds the research institute.
As he writes, all this can be explained by one of the biggest neglects of Hungarian political representatives: "the public debate on the Roma issue was left by representatives of public life to representatives of radical and extremist political groups, who could build a political strategy on the Roma-Hungarian contradiction".
This exacerbates the problem, prevents normal dialogue, empowers extremists and increases the likelihood of violent conflict, the institute said.
In addition, according to the research institute, the activities of the Hungarian Guard, influenced by the great attention of both domestic and foreign media, "to a considerable extent have damaged the image of Hungary abroad, especially in terms of faith in the stability of the country and its democratic development".
As part of the reorganization of Hungarian radical and far-right groups, which has been receiving increasing publicity and vehemence since autumn 2006, several organizations have been formed in Hungary since summer 2007, calling themselves "national defense" associations.
"The common feature of these groups is that they define themselves as civil associations, while openly proclaiming - even armed - the readiness of their members to perform defensive tasks (in case of natural disasters, invasion of the homeland, disorder), in addition to referring to the incompetence of the police, army, or state", he adds.
He also notes that all this is done in a way that tries to pack all kinds of political efforts based on society's resistance to politics and parties into civilian clothes.
The emphasis on the civil character and form of the association thus serves not only to avoid the legal obstacles of judicial registration but also as a political strategy.
According to the analysis, the activity of the Hungarian Guard is also a risk-increasing factor in terms of neighbourly relations.
"In recent months, the Hungarian Guard has been identified in several neighboring states as a potential source of danger, and the ultra-nationalist political leaders of some neighboring countries have sought to justify their own anti-Hungarian policies by invoking the formation of the Hungarian Guard.
All of this may affect the political stability of the region", he adds.
According to the research institute, the emergence of the Hungarian Guard in Central and Eastern Europe is not an isolated phenomenon, which has increased political risks for the region as a whole.
The Hungarian Guard's activities, he writes, are similar to those of the Bulgarian National Guard, whose creation was announced in August 2007 by the far-right Bulgarian National Union (BNU).
The background to the emergence of the Bulgarian Guard is the mass Roma riots that broke out in one of Sofia's neighborhoods (Krasna Poljana).
BNU used this to establish the Guard with the aim of the organization being "national defense".
For the past 17 years, she says, Bulgaria has experienced "gypsy terror" but the state has remained passive and indifferent, notes the Political Capital Institute.
It adds that the initiative has provoked a stormy discussion among the Bulgarian public.
The increased risk of ethnic clashes is indicated by the announcement by some Bulgarian Roma organisations that they will form their own guard in response to the sign of resistance.
Since the activities of the Hungarian Guard so far bear similarities to those of the Bulgarian National Guard, it is not excluded that the Hungarian Roma will react to the threat in a similar way, by establishing their own national defence, as we can read in the risk warning prepared by the Political Capital Institute.
Asked by the press office, Attila Juhász, research director of the Political Capital Institute, said: "Risk analysis is one of the activities of the research institute.
