The holidays aren't free everywhere
In Hungary, the days of rest are precisely defined by law and it has become a common practice to move the working days around holidays, which we will see less of in the coming year.
The holidays are not uniform in the European Union or in America.
The Hungarian legal system distinguishes between national and state holidays and days of rest.
The days of rest are usually associated with religious holidays or important historical events.
We also celebrate the New Year: the last day of the old year and the first day of the new year is a working holiday - for the New Year so that people can rest after New Year's Eve.
We have a total of eleven holidays during the year.
National holidays are March 15, celebrating the Revolution of 1848, and October 23, the day of remembrance of the Revolution of 1956.
August 20th is the anniversary of the founding of the state, May 1st is the anniversary of the labor movement, November 1st and 2nd is the anniversary of the death of relatives and friends.
Besides, we have two-day holidays, Easter, Christmas and Christmas.
Since our national, state or religious holidays rarely fall on a weekend, it has become a practice to move the working day forward in cases where we would only work one day before or after a holiday.
The price of extended weekends, of course, is that we stay at work and school the Saturday before.
The date on which we work the day immediately preceding or following the holiday has been regulated for many years by a special decree of the Minister of Labour.
The law applies equally to all employers and their employees, to public servants and to persons in public service.
However, it does not apply to firms and institutions which are in continuous operation or which, for reasons of their purpose, are also working on non-working days.
This year, the working schedule will change only around the end of the year: from December 24, life in the country will almost stop, because according to previous experience, most people will "work" or use the days between Christmas and New Year in advance.
Next year, we're going to have a number of our holidays in the middle of the week, or on the weekend, so there's going to be less of a shift in the workday than this year.
For the first time, the calendar is changed around Labor Day so that workers can stay home for four days straight.
Saturday, April 26th, will be a working day, so that Friday, May 2nd, may be a day of rest.
The next move is due to the holiday of October 23: Saturday, October 18, will be working instead of Friday, October 24.
But the end of the year next year will be able to go entirely in the sign of the holidays, because from December 24th they will have almost everywhere nonstop holidays, even though New Year's Eve falls on Wednesday.
