A Remarkable Repair to the Space Station
It took more than seven hours of work in space for astronaut Scott Parazynski and his crew members from the International Space Station (ISS) to make a remarkable repair to a torn solar panel, necessary for the station's continued scientific activities.
It was a risky spacewalk that set records for the length of time it took to reach the habitable modules, the speed at which it was scheduled, and the amount of "kitty" that the astronauts spent on repairs.
The trouble began on Tuesday as astronauts from the space shuttle Discovery unloaded the Harmony module, a large cylindrical device designed to house a European and Japanese science lab (see box).
This module is a kind of landing dock for the lab modules.
But they need to be able to supply electricity.
The second task of the crew was therefore to relocate the 17 and a half tonne solar module already on the ISS to anchor at its final destination.
After moving it, the crew began laying out the module's 700-foot solar array.
And in it, one of the panels, folding like a pulling harmonica, as a result of the pinching of the cable, was damaged in an area of almost one meter.
Deposition has been suspended to prevent further damage to the panel.
The astronauts, who were originally scheduled to perform a control climb on the Discovery, and then go to repair another solar panel whose rotation system was faulty, were forced to focus on the damaged panel.
And it was Scott Parazynski who was chosen to go fly to the end of the robotic arm of the ship, attached to the station's arm, and perform the repair.
He is one of the best spacewalkers in the United States.
Tall, stout, very nimble, with a very elaborate chest and long arms.
At the age of 46, this original occupation doctor was assigned to "operate" on a "wounded" solar panel.
After examining the damage in detail, he cut the faulty wire and attached a "floor" to the damaged areas.
He was assisted by a second spacewalker who stayed near the balancing chamber, and also from inside, by other astronauts, among them Peggy Witson, the crew chief.
The tool he used, a miniature hockey stick covered with insulation to prevent an electric shock to the solar panels producing several hundred volts, was invented and "cut-and-paste" by astronauts aboard the station.
After the surgery, Scott Parazynski waited until the panel was completely disassembled, then inventoried his tools and returned to the inside of the station.
Yesterday afternoon, the astronauts were enjoying a midday rest before the day when the seven astronauts return to the shuttle Discovery to return to Earth on Wednesday, as scheduled.
