- "Who will be Putin's successor in the presidential office?
The Official Gazette published yesterday the date of the first round of the presidential election, March 2, 2008; candidates can present themselves to the public until December 23.
Vladimir Putin, elected in 2000 and re-elected in 2004, cannot seek a third consecutive term.
But no successor has emerged.
- "What role will Putin play after March?"
He's going to be Prime Minister?
Or the head of the parliamentary majority and the all-powerful United Russia party, which chooses the government and the president?
Either way, the outgoing ruling power will win in a landslide in the parliamentary elections, as well as the presidential elections.
It's a tradition.
"Russians have retained the mentality of the homo sovietica, they do not feel that they are masters of their fate", says sociologist Lev Gudkov, director of the independent Levada Center.
Historian Nikolai Kopossov of St. Petersburg State University notes a more distant connection: civil society in this country, Christianized five centuries after Europe, has been late; that famous community spirit has delayed the formation of individualism.
After the liberal reforms of the 1990s, "Putin has built on a paternalistic model of the state, perfectly accepted by the population, all the more so because this new paternalism has not been accompanied by terror, but by a certain economic prosperity", believes Maria Lipman of the Carnegie Foundation.
Russians today are "voluntarily renouncing personal responsibility", as they demonstrated shortly after the collapse of the Soviet Union.
"What to think about?"
This phenomenon affects all walks of life, including the business world.
Even the bureaucratic elite intends to maintain the status quo: 65 governors (out of a total of 85 heads of Russian regions) run local United Russia candidates.
The new freedoms that have been taken from the West are often, as in the 1990s, synonymous with chaos.
Public opinion is favoring stability.
Also, in the name of stability, Russians will not vote for extremists.
Conclusion by Tamara Cherednichenko, a 54-year-old professor: "What is there to think about?
Those in power aren't so bad, so why change them?"
Memory used
After more than 60 years in a secret regime, the Nazi archives in Bad Arolsen, which document the fates of 17.5 million victims of Hitler's regime, are opening to the public.
The 47 million archival documents stored in a 27 km long area in Bad Arolsen (Hesse) have so far been accessible only for 'humanitarian' purposes, that is, individually and by name, at the request of the former victim or his authorized persons.
In May, 11 nations - including Germany, France, Israel, and the United States - agreed to open the archives to scientists and historians.
As the ratification process of this agreement by all states is complete, the opening became effective yesterday.
The following information is provided for each Member State:
The free access of historians to Bad Arolsen will allow them to examine "especially the transfers of prisoners, the population of the camps and the health of forced laborers", explains Reto Meistern, director of the archives managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, several states, including Germany, opposed the opening of these documents to the public because of the sensitive nature of some of the information.
What are the alleged homosexuality or mental disabilities of some of the deportation victims?
The concentration camp or arrest warrant records compiled by the Gestapo were collected after the war for the practical purpose of finding deported or forced to work civilian citizens, to bring them evidence of their internment in order to open the way for their compensation.
Even today, over 300 permanent employees in Bad Arolsen deal with tens of thousands of individual requests.
However, for some in the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen is of limited benefit.
"Nothing fundamentally new can be expected from these documents", said Professor Wolfgang Benz, director of the Center for the Study of Anti-Semitism at Berlin's Technische Universität, in 2006.
