Congress has approved the transposition of MiFID effective November 1
In conjunction with the parliamentary proceedings that ended today with the congressional vote on the novelties incorporated by the Senate into the bill, the government has put in place a public hearing on the regulations that develop the new law, with the goal that both will come into effect before the end of the year.
The representatives of the parties unanimously highlighted the efforts of Members of Parliament and Senators to negotiate and agree on the best standard to guarantee the protection of investors and the detailed regulation of the activities of entities necessary for the efficient functioning of markets.
The MiFID Directive, which amends the Securities Trading Act, provides for the modernisation of financial markets while strengthening investor protection, improving the supervisory powers of the State Securities Market Commission (CNMV) and promoting cooperation between the various supervisory bodies of the European Union.
This new regulation will allow financial advisory services to be provided to both specialist firms and natural or legal persons and creates a new type of financial advisory services firms (ESIS), financial advisory firms (AFI) which will join securities firms, securities brokerage firms and portfolio management companies.
In addition, the number of systems for the execution of transactions in financial instruments is expanding by adding multilateral trading systems and order internalisation systems to regulated secondary markets, which will compete with current stockbrokers.
The law also requires firms providing investment services to disseminate information on the market on key aspects of their business profile, exposure to risk and ways of coping with risk, and requires a report of all transactions carried out to facilitate supervision by the CNMV.
During the Congressional Commerce Committee hearings, several amendments were included, the most prominent of which was to consider securitised debt instruments as a 'complex' financial instrument due to the high investor risk demonstrated by the US subprime experience.
Moreover, the transposition of the Directive was used to lay down the functions which a Bachelor's degree in economics and business administration may fulfil, 30 years after the Royal Decree of 1977 laying down the professional functions reserved for economists.
The Senate also considered the creation of new professions in the financial sector, such as an intermediary who will work externally, will not require authorisation from the CNMV and will be able to provide product trading and client acquisition services for various investment firms simultaneously.
