What kind of insurance is right for me?
Car insurance, which protects the driver in the event of an accident, is a considerable expense, which depends on various factors such as age, status, gender, length of driving licence, type of vehicle to be insured or its use, etc.
Having a car is just the beginning.
Choosing the right car insurance is even more difficult than choosing a car model.
First of all, we need to be clear about what we're talking about.
Car insurance is an agreement between the insurance company and the insured person.
This commitment takes the form of an insurance contract which provides that the insurer will receive an agreed sum of insurance in exchange for taking responsibility for the payment of the damage in the event of an insured event.
The insurable is the price of the insurance, which is determined by various factors such as age, condition, sex, length of holding a driving licence, type of vehicle insured or its use, etc.
Insurance companies base their prices on statistics, so the greater the probability of an accident, the higher the insurance rate.
For this reason, both men and women over 25 years of age have to pay lower premiums, as statistics show that they have a lower risk index due to their caution.
Similarly, insurance companies have concluded that married people have fewer crashes than single drivers.
The way a vehicle is used will affect the frequency of its use and thus the likelihood of it being involved in an accident.
The more you drive, the more likely it is.
There are many variables that insurance companies consider when determining the price of a policy.
Therefore, the driver must study the situation carefully in order to choose the insurance that best fits his profile.
Here we will show the most important variables for choosing a type of insurance that not only satisfies the type of policyholder but also provides a reasonable price.
People under 25 face various disadvantages, such as little driving experience and a short driving record, when they want to buy insurance at an affordable price.
Although all-risk insurance is ideal for good coverage, there are cheaper options.
The most cautious drivers can choose to take out premium-rate all-risk insurance to get all-risk coverage at a more affordable price.
This type of contract would presuppose the participation of the client in the payment of the insurance event.
"The part of the payment of the insurance event that the client will provide will be set in advance when determining the price of the insurance premium, which will be higher the lower the co-participation would be", explains Luis Noguera, CEO of First Europe in Spain, an online insurance intermediary.
Another option is to extend the insurance coverage to other road users, so that the client is insured against damage caused to other persons, but not against damage to his own car.
In addition, he would be insured against theft, fire, and loss of the vehicle.
Recommended
If you are under 25, try to be as careful as possible to avoid accidents, as this will affect your bonus and reduce future premiums.
A bonus is a reduction in the basic rate that an insurance company has.
On the other hand, the minus is an increase in the basic rate.
"Bonus and loss will depend on the insurance company and its profits.
If the insurance company has had a good year, it can afford to raise the bonus", explains Noguera.
After 25 years, drivers have an easier time getting insurance, because their client risk index is lowered by experience.
For this reason, it is highly recommended to take out insurance against all risks and rebates.
"Young people usually cannot use their experience when an accident happens, even when driving", says the director of a European company in Spain, adding that most accidents occur in the second year of driving, when the "fear of the novice" has been overcome.
However, if the client is married but does not yet have children, it is better to take out insurance against all risks, if his financial situation allows it.
Families with children are considered by insurance companies to be the lowest risk-indicator clientele and therefore their premiums will be lower.
In this case, the best insurance would be an all-risk insurance with a premium discount (which could be EUR 300) or with a high premium, the insurance extended to other road users, starting from the third year of the vehicle purchase.
"Their driving is quieter and their purchasing power is higher, so they can afford the luxury of getting the highest discount", notes Luis Noguera.
Pensioners are advised to take out a full risk insurance with a reduced premium (EUR 150) or an insurance extended to other road users if a high premium is achieved.
It must be said that automobile insurance is important not only because it protects the driver in the event of an accident but also because it is a considerable expense, which is a good reason to make a careful study of the insurance options that would best suit your personal situation.
