Concerns over new gas dispute between Russia and Ukraine
The ongoing dispute between Russia and Ukraine over gas prices increases the risk that Russian supplies of gas to Western Europe may be affected.
Most Russian fuel exported to the European Union (EU) is piped through Ukraine, and any dispute between the two countries is closely monitored.
Kiev has warned that if Moscow raises gas prices for Ukraine, it will charge Russia higher transit fees.
A previous dispute between the two last year reduced deliveries to EU countries.
The latest dispute between Kiev and Moscow comes as the Ukrainian government and Russia's state-owned gas monopoly, Gazprom, try to agree on how much Ukraine will have to pay for Russian gas in 2008.
Gazprom says it will have to charge Ukraine more, as it has agreed to pay up to 50% more for gas it gets from neighboring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say this could mean Ukraine will have to pay 40% more for its supplies from Gazprom.
"It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important gas transit countries in the negotiations", Ukraine's Economy Minister Anatoly Kinach told Reuters.
'The changes in gas prices should undoubtedly be linked to our arguments regarding the amount of the transit fees (to Western Europe) via Ukraine.'
The last major dispute between Moscow and Kiev caused a reduction in supplies from Gazprom to Ukraine in January 2006.
This caused a sharp drop in exports to Western Europe, which led to a sharp increase in prices.
Russian gas accounts for one quarter of the European Union's gas supply.
Russia has the largest gas reserves in the world, but a large part of it remains underutilized.
As a result, Gazprom is supplementing its own gas supplies from Turkmenistan and other former Soviet Central Asian republics.
The NHS "must control foreign workers"
The Comptroller said that the NHS chamber in Scotland needs to improve criminal record checks on non-European staff.
The recommendation from the head of the Supreme Audit Office, Robert Black, came after a foreign doctor working in Scotland was linked to the June attacks at Glasgow Airport.
Mr Black is also concerned that the Scottish NHS does not have a clear picture of the number of foreign staff it employs.
But his report emphasized that the other key checks were fine on a sample of five health departments.
The President of the Supreme Audit Office was interested in recruiting staff from outside the European Economic Area immediately after the June attacks at Glasgow Airport.
Bilal Abdullah, a 28-year-old Iraqi doctor at the Royal Alexandra Hospital in Paisley, was detained at the airport after someone crashed a jeep into the main terminal building door.
He was one of three doctors who appeared in the Central Criminal Court on video surveillance charged with being involved in attempted bombings in the UK.
The NHS Chambers are expected to check foreign staff for qualifications, experience and authorisation to work in the UK before they are hired.
Although Disclosure Scotland is used by the Scottish Health Commission for criminal record checks, the agency has no authority to obtain such information outside the UK.
The report of the President of the Supreme Control Board says, among other recommendations, that the commission should be guided by the guidelines of the Criminal Records Bureau, which helps employers with controls in several countries.
"Although we found that some of the personnel records contained evidence of these checks, they are not carried out regularly", the report stated.
Mr Black said that the Scottish NHS was in much the same way as its own pre-employment screening policy, but added: 'Our report highlights areas where the system could be improved to ensure accurate information on the numbers of overseas staff is available.'
BMA Scotland chairman Dr Peter Terry said it was "highly unlikely" that pre-employment checks would identify potential NHS staff who could commit an act of terrorism in the future.
"The report suggests that the current pre-employment checks in the Scottish NHS are working well and it is unclear what additional value the recalls will bring", he said.
The Scottish Health Authority has announced that it currently has 1,161 foreign workers, the vast majority of whom are doctors and nurses.
However, the president of the Supreme Control Authority warned that these figures may be higher also because the commissions had problems identifying staff with residence permits.
The survey also found that the established control procedures at NHS authorities in Ayrshire and Arran, Grampian, Greater Glasgow and Clyde, Lanarkshire and Lothian are largely followed.
They included passport checks, work permits and qualifications.
The Scottish Government is currently reviewing the policy and guidelines for pre-employment checks for foreign NHS workers.
Health Minister Nicola Sturgeon said: "I wanted to do this job immediately after the terrorist attack at Glasgow Airport".
She also added that the Scottish Government, in consultation with the Health Committees, will consider the recommendations of this report and ensure that best practice is reflected in the updated pre-employment screening guidelines for all staff - including foreigners - that it plans to issue next month.
