The climate on Venus may be a glimpse into Earth's future
Scientists announced yesterday that Venus may once have been a pleasant place to live.
Data from an orbiting European station shows the planet is even more like Earth's mischievous twin than previously thought.
Venus is Earth's nearest planetary neighbor.
The two worlds are about the same size and orbit similar orbits, but Venus is a little closer to the Sun.
Scientists now believe that billions of years ago, Venus had conditions similar to those on Earth and could have been habitable.
But the runaway greenhouse effect caused by carbon dioxide, atmospheric erosion from solar radiation and a slower rotation sent the Venusians down a very different evolutionary path.
Today, the planet is without water, the surface temperature is hot enough to melt lead, and it is ravaged by storms and hurricane-force winds.
Findings from the European Space Agency's Venus Express probe, which has studied the planet for a year, offer a fresh look at how Earth might evolve in the event of catastrophic climate change.
Professor Fred Taylor, of the University of Oxford's Physics Department and one of the leaders of the Venus Express mission, said: "It is becoming increasingly clear why the climate on Venus is so different from that on Earth, even though the planets themselves are quite similar in other ways.
"Our new data allows us to construct a scenario in which Venus began as Earth, perhaps with a habitable environment, billions of years ago".
