But the beleaguered Gordon Brown could have done without the discovery that some wealthy businessman had been concealing £650,000 ($1.3 million) in contributions to the ruling Labour Party under the names of other people for four years, and that the party had not reported it.
Two months ago, when the Prime Minister avoided calling an election and insulted British intelligence by claiming that this decision was not influenced by the polls, there was hope that he would provide a resilient and effective government.
Instead of the increasingly witty words of the Liberal Democrat acting chairman, the once feared Mr. Brown has gone from Stalin to Mr. Bean.
The reckless rescue of the troubled bank Northern Rock has revealed weakness in management and poor judgment under fire.
The ill-conceived proposals to change the tax code have brought the corporations together against the government.
The leak of 25 million people's personal data exposed unimaginable administrative indiscretions.
A trio of retired generals started a rebellion in the House of Lords, protesting against cuts in military spending, claiming that being commander of the armed forces was a part-time job.
Now here are the many-faced gifts from David Abrahams; Peter Watt, the Labour general secretary (and their former internal disciplinary warden), has already resigned.
None of this means that Mr. Brown is inevitably heading for his end.
Even so, governments can reach a tipping point beyond which they find governance difficult.
People don't trust politicians and they don't like them, but they usually shift their distrust when a new party takes over.
When it seems clear that a prime minister is unlikely to make a difference, and may not even be in office for long, this displacement goes away: the state administration becomes hollow, ministers start to do briefings, the press searches for bad news, and the government becomes unfocused and defensive.
In one respect, Mr. Brown's position is particularly challenging, since he cannot take on the role of the new broomstick, as opposed to other political leaders.
As much as he'd like to distance himself from Tony Blair, he was his first officer.
For example, the Northern Rock problems and the IRS records are tied to decisions Mr. Brown made as Secretary of the Treasury.
And even if he wasn't directly involved in the Blairite scandals, such as the long-running investigation into party funding caused by "money for money" scandals, voters can safely assume that he was.
Still, Mr. Brown's troubles are not as bad as they seem.
These excesses are not as terrible as the conservatives make them out to be.
As far as Mr. Bean is concerned, no one has died or been deliberately deceived.
And the cure, painful as it may be, is to provide what Mr. Brown's Stalinist tendencies have always promised: a reliable, firm and lightly brutal rule.
The recent political gift-giving riot is a good example.
Mr. Garboid Abrahams, who equates his donations with charity, says he didn't want any publicity for his charity.
That may be true, but the decision wasn't his.
The laws against the anonymity of major political donors are clear, and they exist for a simple reason: the public has a right to know who might be buying access to those who govern the country.
Mr. Watt, who said he knew about Mr. Abrahams's move, but didn't know it was illegal, will certainly be questioned thoroughly; so will Jon Mendlesohn, the main Labour fundraiser, who learned of the devious gifts in October.
But Mr. Brown is not implicated; there is nothing to suggest that he knew about the scams, even though the bulk of the payments occurred after his June appointment.
The Prime Minister has done half the work.
The court very quickly condemned this violation of the law by its own party, but diluted its determination by looking for a proven instrument, a commission to investigate the matter - led, moreover, by a retired bishop and a judge.
In this case, the lessons are not difficult.
If there's been a breach of the law, it's a matter for the police.
And there are other things Mr. Brown needs to do, like find a permanent chairman for the independent Committee on Standards in Public Life, which has been without one for six months, and move forward with real reform of political party funding.
That would require Labour, which is in trouble, to cooperate with the Tories and perhaps to give up their special financial relationship with the union - a bitter pill for a dedicated party member like Mr Brown.
But he should face some simple facts.
The Conservatives now have a decent lead in the polls; he has two years to win back the voters; and the only way to extort victory is with unassailable integrity and high competence.
Card sharks
Is the subprime mortgage crisis affecting the U.S. credit card market?
When there's blood in the water, the dorsal fins naturally start to flutter around excitedly.
Now that the U.S. real estate market is crashing, predators have turned their attention to the U.S. credit card market.
Goldman Sachs analysts say that credit card losses could reach $99 billion if other forms of consumer credit were to be infected by subprime mortgages.
The voltage signals are obvious.
The number of defaults (over 30 days late) and of written-offs (bills considered by the provider to be unenforceable) is increasing.
HSBC last month announced that it had lost $1.4 billion in the U.S. consumer credit market, partly due to insolvent credit card loans.
It's too early to panic.
The accounts written and the defaulted are still small.
According to Moody's, the default rate of 3,89% in the third quarter was almost one percentage point below the average.
The deteriorating rates can be partly explained by technical reasons.
The change in the US personal bankruptcy laws in 2005 led to a sharp decline in the number of reported bankruptcies, which account for a large proportion of credit card losses; the number of reports (and thus the number of write-offs) would therefore rise regardless of whether general conditions for lenders have worsened.
The industry also has a good repayment rate, which shows how much consumers pay off their debts each month.
And trust in securities backed by credit cards is solid, despite the paralysis in other corners of structured finance.
Mr. Dennis Moroney of TowerGroup predicts that their emissions for 2007 will be 25% higher than last year.
Direct pathways for infection between the subprime mortgage crisis and the credit card market certainly exist: when loans to real estate assets dry up, consumers are more likely to borrow via credit cards.
However, credit card issuers look at cash flow rather than collateral, so falling home prices may not necessarily change lenders' credibility.
They may even be advantageous to the lender.
The motivation of consumers to repay mortgages declines when the value of their property falls below the value of the loan; as a result, card debt moves up the list of priorities for repayment.
Card issuers can also respond more quickly and flexibly to more volatile conditions than mortgage lenders by changing interest rates or borrowing limits.
This should, in theory, reduce the risks of rapid price changes of the products in question.
"We're not going to just one fine morning and reassess all of the loans", says Gary Perlin, chief financial officer of Capital One.
Although the risk of a sub-prime explosion is low, the danger of a gradual weakening is far more real.
If lower house prices and debt reduction push America into recession, the credit card industry will face a darker future.
Watch out for those dorsal fins.
British bankers plead guilty to Enron
Three British bankers who were due to stand trial for their roles in a fraud involving former Enron CFO Andrew Fastow changed their plea to guilty on Wednesday.
David Bermingham, Giles Darby and Gary Mulgrew originally pleaded not guilty to seven counts of fraud, in which they were accused of participating with Fastow in a financial fraud in 2000 -- enriching themselves at the expense of their employers.
They were due in court in January.
However, during their trial before U.S. District Judge Ewing Werlein, Jr., each of them confessed to one fraud.
The case of the three former senior executives of Greenwich NatWest, a unit of Royal Bank of Scotland Group PLC, was front-page news for two years during the issuing process.
In the United States, their case is one of the unfinished parts of the investigation that began after the Enron crash in 2001.
The charges brought against them in 2002 alerted Mr. Fastow that he was the target of a government investigation into the Enron collapse.
The indictment against the bankers -- who earned the nickname "The NatWest Three" -- alleges that they came to Houston in 2000 to plot a fraud with Fastow and his former chief associate, Michael Kopper.
Greenwich NatWest invested in a subsidiary of Enron controlled by Fastow, who was the architect of the Enron fraud scandal that spiralled Enron into bankruptcy.
In early 2002, the bank valued its stake in the branch at zero, but our three British people knew that it was in fact of considerable value.
A company controlled by Kopper bought the bank's interest in this branch for $1 million.
The bankers in question paid Kopper $250,000 for a stake in this company.
The indictment alleges that Fastow falsely informed Enron that the energy company would pay $20 million for its stake in this subsidiary of Greenwich NatWest.
But the 20 million actually went to those British bankers, Fastow and others.
The bankers were awarded $7.3 million, according to the indictment, and Fastow, Kopper and others were awarded approximately $12.3 million.
In January 2004, Fastow pleaded guilty to two counts of conspiracy for his role in the collapse of Enron.
The British trio were arrested three months later.
Fastow is currently serving a six-year sentence in a federal prison in Louisiana.
Kopper is serving a sentence of three years and one month at the Texarkanan facility.
All three Britons were free on $1 million bail, which ordered them to remain in the United States for the forthcoming trial.
Enron, once the seventh largest company in the country, collapsed into bankruptcy in December 2001 after years of accounting tricks no longer allowed it to hide billions in debt or report failing speculation as profitable.
The collapse has wiped out thousands of jobs, over $60 billion in market value, and over $2 billion in pension insurance.
Enron founder Kenneth Lay and former chief executive Jeffrey Skilling were convicted last year for their roles in the company's collapse.
Skilling is serving more than a 24-year sentence.
Lay's convictions on conspiracy, fraud and other charges were overturned after he died of a heart attack last year.
Moscow's not-powerlessness
The price of a Gulfstream G550 with a Rolls-Royce engine and enough fuel to fly nonstop from Moscow to Los Angeles starts at $54 million.
For some of the Russian rich, it's a small change.
"It can carry up to 18 passengers", says Dan Firer, a representative of Gulfstream.
"But none of them are interested in so many positions because it's for the close family or the company president".
Mr. Firer was sitting at the Gulfstream booth last Friday at the Millionaire's Fair, a four-day orgy of extravagant consumption at the mammoth exhibition center on the outskirts of the capital.
Besides Gulfstream, over 200 other luxury suppliers set up their booths, hoping to lure newly wealthy Russians to everything from mahogany-laden yachts to diamond-encrusted car windows that 50 Cent wouldn't be ashamed of.
Mr. Firer was looking carefully at the bright orange Porsche in the next booth.
"That's a nice car, but we're up against the fives and the tens", he said.
"Russia is the second largest market for private aircraft after the United States".
Oil waves are pouring money into the Russian capital, just like they did in Dallas.
"We went through the same stage in the 1980s when some Americans became enormously wealthy and moved to Europe, where they were looked at as materialists", said Marshall Goldman, a fourth-year student at Harvard's Davis Center for Russian and Eurasian Studies.
Like the Saudi spenders of the 1970s and the Japanese of the 1990s, the Russians are becoming the world's most prominent spenders.
The most exclusive luxury brands are looking for a share of this Klondike.
Elsewhere in Moscow this week, a conference of luxury industry leaders, Donatello Versace, Tom Ford and Bernard Arnault, chairman of LVMH Group, came together to exchange ideas on how to sell expensive goods in markets like the Russian one.
(The conference is organized by The International Herald Tribune, owned by The New York Times Company.)
According to Forbes magazine's list of the world's richest people, Russia has 53 billionaires with a combined net worth of $282 billion.
Moreover, the country's leading research institute, the Center for Economic and Financial Research, has released a report on the development of personal wealth in the former Soviet Union, which shows that there are 103,000 "second-tier" millionaires in Russia, with a total net worth of $670 billion.
(The World Bank reports that in 2005, 15.8 percent of Russians lived below the poverty line.)
"There are hundreds of millionaires in Moscow -- and that's why we're all here", said Nicole Marais, sales and marketing representative at David Morris's London jewelry store.
She was at the show for the first time, along with the Russian distributor of the brand, Soho Jewelry Group.
"All women are perfectly groomed and men are each for a fortune".
As they strolled around in evening robes on Sunday night, Evgenia Yumatov, 21, and Svetlana Turkovkovkov, five years her senior, declared themselves and their clients millionaires.
"I've been looking at these cars and I can't decide between an Infiniti, a Mercedes and a Porsche", said Ms. Yumatova, who dressed in designer clothes like a veteran red carpet, next to which Joan Rivers looks like a housewife.
The fair seemed to be aimed primarily at the newly rich, brand-driven Russian shoppers who are willing to sit in traffic for hours to walk through a warehouse that screams Cadillac Escalade, platinum fish, Mövenpick ice cream, custom-made pool tables, Dubai apartments, Gund plushes and propellers.
Members of the general public could buy tickets for 30 euros ($44.57).
"The Russians are interested in which brand is the most expensive and the best", said Mr. Gijrath, who patriotically occupied the booth of Dutch porcelain manufacturer Royal Delft in front of a life-size, hand-painted blue-tiled reproduction of Rembrandt's painting.
"Of course, the Russians are more interested in the gold".
Indeed, local vendors say that Russians with old money (by Russian standards, 10 to 15 years old) have already moved from flashy logs to little-known limited-edition brands that would never make it to the shopping fair.
Still, thousands of people, whether millionaires, envoys of millionaires or simple tourists, flooded the fairgrounds every day.
And some of them were shopping.
On the first day of the exhibition, last Thursday, Roman Ershov, the local general manager of King Koil Beds, reported that he sold two sets of silk, cashmere and cotton mattresses, with gold threads, for $70,000 each.
Also on the first day, Mikhail Lyubimov, sales manager for A1 Moto, which outfits high-end cars with high-end alarms, said that his company sold a bright orange Porsche for $170,000 to a Russian millionaire.
On Sunday afternoon, Andrei Karapetian, president of L.A. Connection, a luxury car customizer, announced that he had sold three Rolls-Royce Phantoms in the form of linked chain bracelets for $55,000.
He showed the reporter a car wheel designed for a Russian casino owner, which had a casing covered in Swarovski crystals to look like a roulette wheel.
Price: 22,000 dollars for four of these.
"The Russian millionaire who wants ostrich skin wheels or a portrait of his wife made of cubic zirconia doesn't need to ride those wheels", said Mr Karapetian.
"He stores them in his garage for 30 to 40 cars".
Although many of his Russian clients are wealthy, Mr. Karapetian said the phrase "Russian millionaire" doesn't mean anything exclusive these days, given the huge increase in local property prices.
"If you bought an apartment in Moscow three or four years ago, you're probably already a millionaire, at least on paper, if not in cash", he said.
"There are more of them than you think".
Those who are not millionaires could at least feign wealth at a stand operated by the Russian asset management firm Alliance Continental.
The company erected four red British-style telephone booths filled with piles of counterfeit bills worth a million dollars.
Azad Karryev, the company's marketing manager, said that his team had printed 500,000 fake bills for the Millionaires Fair.
Passengers stopped to throw around piles of money, or to have friends take their cell phone photos of them relaxing in the middle of alternative wealth, or to simply pocket a few million.
"You know, in Moscow, everyone can feel like a millionaire", Mr. Karryev said.
