Venus is the infernal twin of Earth
Despite its hostile atmosphere, Venus is more Earth-like than previously thought. The European Venus Express spacecraft has detected phenomena that occur on Earth in winter: lightning in the atmosphere and whirlpoles at the poles.
For nearly three decades, scientists have suspected that Venus flashes.
The European spacecraft Venus Express has now provided evidence - electromagnetic waves on the edge of the atmosphere, with lightning flashing from cloud to cloud at about 35 miles [56 km] above the surface of Venus, writes Christopher Russell of the University of California, Los Angeles, in the scientific journal Nature.
The famous theory of primordial matter suggests that lightning may have given rise to life on Earth, and that storms triggered reactions in the oceans that resulted in the formation of amino acids, the building blocks of life.
This was not the case on Venus: "If there was life there, it must have been a long time ago", explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution of Washington.
Today, life on the surface of Venus would be almost impossible, with an atmosphere about 100 times denser than Earth's, and sometimes reaching temperatures of 500 degrees Celsius.
"Venus may be the hell twin of Earth, but it's the hell twin", Russell said.
Why Venus, which is so similar in mass and size to Earth, began to evolve in a completely different way is the fundamental question of the ESA mission.
Since no probe has been sent to Venus for study purposes alone since the early 1990s, the launch of Venus Express in November 2005 marked a milestone in the exploration of the planet.
According to scientists, the latest research, reported in several articles of Nature, has not only highlighted the uniqueness of Venus in the solar system.
"They also show that our neighboring planet is more Earthlike than previously thought", Esa said.
In addition to the already known winds at the North Pole, scientists have found a cloud vortex at the South Pole that spins much faster.
The phenomenon is reminiscent of the air currents in Earth's northern hemisphere, writes a research team led by Giuseppe Piccioni of the Instituto di Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica, Italy.
The second innermost planet in our solar system has almost the same mass as Earth and is nearly as large at 12,100 kilometers in diameter.
This planet, known as Dawn or Evening, orbits the sun in just over 225 days.
But it rotates much more slowly on its axis, taking one day on Venus to equal 243 days on Earth.
Although Venus does not resemble Earth in its surface temperature of 1,300 degrees Fahrenheit [460°C] and pressure of 92 bars, scientists believe that the two planets were formed under very similar conditions.
Water accumulated on both, but on Earth it remained in the oceans, while Venus evaporated into space.
Whereas carbon dioxide on Earth is bound up in carbonates on Earth, on Venus it makes up most of the atmosphere.
