These aren't Warhol boxes.
Anyone who combines the words Sweden and wooden boxes is not thinking of Andy Warhol, but Ike.
Or is it?
The wooden boxes now produced in Sweden cast dark shadows on Warhol's list of works.
Most of the 94 Stockholm-type "Brillo boxes" on his list are forgeries.
After the Swedish newspaper Expressen raised doubts a few months ago about the authenticity of Warhol's 1968 "Brillo boxes", an internal investigation by Moderna Museet in Stockholm has come up with a disconcerting result: the six "Brillo boxes" donated to Moderna Museet in 1995 by its former director Pontus Hultén are copies - as are most of the other "Brillo boxes" of the Stockholm type that circulate on the international art market.
The events that preceded it are a tangled, confusing chain of artistic and curatorial events.
Warhol made his first Brillo boxes in New York in 1964, painting the wooden boxes based on the red-and-white design of Brillo's soap-powder paper boxes.
An exhibition of his works at the Moderna Museet in 1968 featured - with Warhol's approval - hundreds of Brillo cardboard cases, which were not made by Warhol (for financial reasons) but were delivered directly from the Brillo factory.
It wasn't about the artwork, it was about the models, the exhibits.
Warhol apparently also gave permission in 1968 to have several wooden Brillo cases made in Sweden, but these are not exhibited in the Moderna Museet.
Witnesses at the time now speak of 15 boxes that then rightfully entered art and auction history as authorized originals - "Andy Warhol's Brillo Boxes" with the Stockholm type.
Some of these have been sold at auctions for over $100,000.
The problem now is that the legendary director of the museum, Pontus Hultén, later falsely claimed that in 1968 about 100 boxes had been made and displayed in Sweden, which Warhol then left to him.
In fact, 105 Hultén boxes were made in Malmö for the exhibition in Petrograd only in 1990.
By that time, Warhol had been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, chief curator of the Moderna Museet, examined, in addition to the six Brillo boxes owned by the museum, three Brillo boxes from a Swedish private collection, two of which were made in Sweden in 1968 and had their base plates painted and coated with a brush and painted with oil white.
The structure of the 1990 copies, on the other hand, shows that the paint was applied directly to the plywood by the painter's roller without any prior basic coating - and it is an acrylic paint rather than an oil paint.
"These boxes were not authorized by the artist and should be removed from Warhol's official Brillo box list", Moderna Museet director Lars Nittve said: "Unless the Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board in New York reaches a different conclusion, Moderna Museet will have to classify six of its exhibition boxes as 'exhibition material - copies.'"
Back in July, the Authentication Board announced that it would be addressing these "major allegations" that were raised in the soap powder boxes case.
But the organization has remained silent.
